fields.description: Peace Arch Park is accessed from Highway 99 near the Canada-US border. The directory board has ample clear and level space around it, and includes maps of the park and of the general area.
The parking lot for Peace Arch Park is located behind the duty free shop, off of Beach Avenue. Of the more than 150 parking stalls, none are designated as accessible.

The main access route connects the parking lot to the other main areas of the park which include the washrooms, Heritage Hall, the viewpoint, picnic area, and the Peace Arch. The route itself is fully paved, has adequate width and minimal slope, and is generally in good repair.

Peace Arch offers over 30 picnic tables spread out in different areas of the park. About half are in a large grassy field connected to the parking lot, requiring travel over the grass to reach them. None of these tables have accessible overhanging ends. The tables near the washroom building are on a flat and level concrete surface. One table in this area has an accessible overhang, as well as a section of the bench cut out for wheelchair access.

Garbage cans and recycling receptacles are conveniently located throughout the park, found at the major access routes and picnic areas. Some bins are large garbage can-style and are not securely fastened to the ground, particularly the ones by the washroom building.

There are two water fountains in the picnic areas, located in a grassy field away from an accessible pathway. They are built of stone, and require a step up onto the stone platform to access the fountain.
Benches are scattered around the viewing areas of the park. All of these benches are on firm and level ground, have a back rest and at least one arm rest, and are secured to the ground.

Peace Arch Park has one washroom building, located in the middle of the picnic areas, and off the main access route to the Peace Arch. This building offers an accessible toilet stall, with a wide outward swinging door and ample clear space beside the toilet. Horizontal grab bars are mounted beside and behind the toilet. The toilet paper dispenser is closed-roll style, mounted forward of the side grab bar. The sink area includes three sinks, minimal counter space, and no knee clearance under the counter. Taps require grip and dexterity to operate. Soap dispensers are push-activated, and are mounted quite high above the sinks. A hand dryer is also push-activated, and is mounted just to the left of the sinks, with clear space in front of it. This building also includes a baby change table.

The Heritage Hall is available to rent for events. The area around the building is paved and level, with doorways that have a width of 915 mm. Both the main area and kitchen are spacious and level, with concrete flooring in the whole building. A fridge and full kitchen are offered. There is also an exterior picnic area outside the Heritage Hall, which includes 19 tables, 2 large charcoal grills, a food prep station and full sink area. A big overhang provides protection while cooking your food.

There are two main viewing areas, both of which offer a south-facing view of the Peace Arch. These viewpoints are split up into two sections; one is near the Heritage Hall building, and the other is on the east side of the highway, off of Peace Arch Drive. There are ten benches altogether in these two locations. The benches are located on firm and level concrete slabs, but are not connected to accessible pathways.

Clear Creek Campground is accessed directly from Columbia Valley Road. There is a standard BC Parks sign at the entrance with large letters and clear colour contrasting. There are yellow security gates at the entrance/exit. The directory board just inside the entrance has level access and includes general information about the area.

This campground provides a hard gravel surface on all the campground roads, including into the campsites themselves. Access routes to the washroom buildings offer a paved surface with a good cross slope, but may have minor surface unevenness. A boulder in the path to the washroom building limits the width of this pathway. Pathways to pit toilets may have slopes greater than 8%, and may not be firm and stable in all weather conditions.

Clear Creek campground offers 84 vehicle accessible campsites. Each site has a picnic table without accessible overhang, fire pit, and enough room for multiple tents. The surface for every campsite is compacted gravel and dirt, both in the campground and on the access routes.
Water standpipes are located throughout the campground, generally on firm and level ground.
Garbage and recycling receptacles are provided throughout the campground. All are standard wildlife-proof design, and may or may not be operable for people with limited dexterity.

Clear Creek Campground offers a number of pit toilets, located on paths that are generally firm and stable, but may have slopes greater than 8%. The concrete pad at the door often creates a slight threshold. Doors are wide, and open outwards. Interior dimensions are approximately 1.5 x 1.5 m. Grab bars are installed behind and beside the toilet. Toilet paper dispensers are closed-roll style, and mounted forward of the side grab bar.

Clear Creek Campground has two washroom buildings, centrally located in two of the loops of the campground. Privacy screens at the building entrance creates a tight right angle to access the entry door. Both buildings offer an accessible toilet stall, as well as an accessible shower stall. In the washroom building in the north loop, open transfer space is limited by an inward-swinging door in the women’s side, and the toilet paper dispenser in the men’s side. Grab bars are mounted beside the toilet, but not always behind. Toilet paper dispensers are closed-roll style. Sinks and counters in the main area of the building do not have clear knee space beneath them. Signage for these building is colour contrasted and uses either words or symbols, but does not indicate that the buildings include accessibility features.

Accessible shower stalls are included in the two washroom buildings in this campground. Doorways into the shower stall in the building near campsite 9 are less than 850 mm wide. Shower heads are mounted high on the wall, and are not adjustable in height. Controls are lever style, but are also mounted too high for anyone in a seated position. Horizontal grab bars are install on two walls, including the wall beneath the shower head, and a large fold-down bench is also placed below the shower head as well.

Honeymoon Bay Group Campsite is accessed directly from Columbia Valley Highway, with a clear BC Parks sign at the entrance. There is a yellow security gate with a reflective closed sign. Another sign indicates that this area is for registered guests only.
Public parking is available. There are no designated accessible stalls.

This group campsite is located on steep terrain and, as a result, exterior pathways often have slopes of as high as 25%. Surfaces vary from natural materials to hard-packed gravel or pavement that may be cracked in areas. Widths of pathways vary, but may be as narrow as 920 mm.
The campsites are flat and the ground is firm and stable. Each of the two sites can accommodate 15 to 45 people.
Picnic tables with accessible an overhang are currently not available at this location.

Garbage and recycling receptacles are located in each of the two group sites. They have firm and level ground for approach from the front and sides. All are standard wildlife-proof design that may be difficult to operate for people with limited dexterity.

There is a washroom and shower building at this site, which includes a designated accessible stall. Interior dimensions of this stall are large. An angled grab bar is incorrectly installed beside the toilet; there is no rear grab bar. Toilet paper dispenser is closed-roll style.

The access route to the picnic shelter has a slope that exceeds 8%, and there is a threshold from the pathway to the surface of the shelter. None of the tables in this shelter have accessible overhangs. Floor surface is level concrete that is in good repair.

Westside Group Campsites is accessed from Columbia Valley Highway along Parmenter Road, with no signage to indicate the turn-off, and no further signage until the security gate. The security gate remains locked, with access allowed only for rental groups. The campsite is a further ten minute drive up the road.
Group campsite includes picnic tables which do not have extended overhangs. Standard fire pit available near picnic area.
There are a number of picnic tables in this area, none of which have accessible overhangs. They are located on hard-packed gravel, and have ample clear space around them.

Garbage and recycling receptacles are standard wildlife-proof design, that may be difficult to operate for people with limited dexterity. They are located on uneven ground and do not have clear level access from front or sides.
There is one pit toilet located up a steep gravel slope. There is limited clear ground in front of the door. The door is wide and swings out.

The area outside the security gate near the quarry is used as a parking lot for bike trails. There is a steep and narrow side pathway to get past the security gate, and a porta-pit toilet just on the other side of the gate. From here, it is approximately a ten-minute drive or a half hour walk to the group campsite. The road is wide, level, firm and stable the whole way.

Delta Grove Campground is accessed from Columbia Valley Highway, with a clear parks sign at the entrance. The entrance has a yellow security gate, and a directory board that includes a map of the campground. Concrete parking curbs limit access to the directory board.

Exterior pathways in this campground are mostly paved and have minimal slope and a width of over 1 m. Some sections of the paths include root upheavals. The roadway is also used as an exterior pathway, and includes speed bumps that extend the full width of the road.

Delta Grove Campground offers 58 vehicle accessible campsites. The surface for every campsite is compacted gravel which make it easy to maneuver, with enough room for multiple tents. Most sites also have electrical hookups. Each site has a picnic table, none of which have accessible overhangs. Fire pits are standard design and include cooking grids.
Water stand pipes are located throughout the campground.
There are garbage and recycling receptacles located throughout the campground. They have the standard wildlife-proof design that may or may not be usable for people with limited dexterity.

There are a number of pit toilets in this campground. Pathways are compacted gravel, and the concrete pad at the door may be slightly higher than the pathway. Doors are wide and open out, interior dimensions are 1.5 x 1.5 m or more, and grab bars are installed behind and beside the toilet. Toilet paper dispensers are closed-roll style, and are mounted forward of the grab bar.

This campground offers one washroom building that is located in the centre of the campground. These washrooms offer an accessible toilet stall in each of the men’s and women’s areas. Doors are wide and swing out, and there is adequate clear space inside the stall. Grab bars are installed behind and beside the toilet. Toilet paper dispensers are closed-roll style, and are mounted forward of the grab bar.

This campground offers one washroom building that is located in the centre of the campground. These washrooms offer an accessible toilet stall as well as an accessible shower stall. The shower head is mounted high on the wall, and is not adjustable or able to be handheld. Horizontal grab bars are installed on two walls, but are not below the shower head.

Delta Grove campground has informational signs that are conveniently located at the main entrance area of the park. The signs have good colour contrast and are easy to read. Smaller signs in the park offer a good contrast and are consistently placed.

Entrance Bay Campground and Picnic Day Use area are both accessed directly from Columbia Valley Road, on opposite sides of the road, shortly after the large entrance sign and gatehouse for Cultus Lake Park. Both the campground and the picnic area have standard BC Parks signs, and yellow security gates. Both entrances include directory boards; the campground board includes a map of the campground. The board in the day use area has limited access due to concrete parking curbs.
Signage for the accessible stalls is limited to white surface markings; there is no vertical signage for these stalls.

The day use area offers ample parking in two large paved parking lots. Six parking stalls are designated as accessible, and are located in various areas of the parking lot. The surface of these stalls is level, firm and stable with no slope. Most accessible stalls have clear access to the main pathway and are close to the washrooms. Some of the accessible stalls have cross-hatched access aisles beside them.
A sign at the gatehouse just before Entrance Bay shows the availability of campsites throughout the park. This sign has good colour contrasting and large font.

Entrance Bay campground provides a compacted gravel and dirt surface on all the campground roads, including into the campsites themselves. Access routes to the washroom buildings are paved and have minimal slope. Access routes in the day use area are paved, and are wide and level. Some areas may be uneven because of root upheavals. Pathways to pit toilets are crushed gravel and may have slight slopes.
One campsite in Entrance Bay is designated as accessible. It includes a picnic table with an accessible overhanging end. The site also includes a standard fire pit.

Entrance Bay Campground offers 52 vehicle accessible campsites, all with room for multiple tents. Each site has a picnic table with no accessible overhang, and a fire pit with a cooking grid. The surface for every campsite is compacted gravel and dirt, both in the campground and on the access routes.
Water stand pipes are located throughout the campground and Day Use area, mostly on firm and level ground, along accessible pathways. Some taps require dexterity and grip to operate.

Many picnic tables are located in the Day Use area, between the parking lot and the beach. Most are located on firm grassy ground, which may be uneven or have some slope. Three tables have accessible overhangs, are mounted on concrete slabs and can be accessed via asphalt pathways from the parking lot. An additional table on an accessible pathway does not have an overhanging end. All tables have ample clear space around them.

Garbage and recycling receptacles are located throughout the campground and day use areas. All have the standard wildlife-proof design, and may or may not be operable by people with limited dexterity. Receptacles are located with clear level ground for front access, and sometimes also side access.
There is at least one bench overlooking the lake in the day use area. It is located in a grassy area that is firm and level. This bench has a back rest, but no arm rests.

The five pit toilets in this part of the park are located along pathways that are hard packed gravel with minimal slope. Concrete pads at the doors may create slight thresholds. Doors are wide, and open outwards. Interior dimensions are approximately 1.5 x 1.5 m. Horizontal grab bars are installed behind the toilet and on the inside of the door. Toilet paper dispenser is closed-roll style and mounted high on the side wall.

This park has two washroom buildings in the campground and two in the Day Use area. Washroom buildings on the campground do not have designated accessible stalls, while those in the Day Use area do. Signage does not indicate which buildings have accessibility features. Accessible stalls include grab bars behind and beside the toilet, and adequate clear space for transferring. Toilet paper dispensers are closed-roll style, and are mounted forward of the side grab bar.
Neither the shower buildings in the campground nor the change rooms in the Day Use area have designated accessible stalls that would accommodate people using wheeled mobility aids.

This campground and day-use area have signs that are conveniently located at the main entrance areas. The signs are clean, easy to read, and they provide all the information you need on the park and surrounding area.

The Day Use area offers two docks that have both fixed and floating sections which offer amazing views of the lake. Both docks are close to picnic tables, benches, and washroom buildings. The approach to these docks is soft pebbly-sand. The transition between the fixed and floating section of the docks has a slope that is well in excess of 8%. There is no seating or shelter at these docks, but picnic tables are nearby.

Jade Bay Boat Launch is accessed from Columbia Valley Road, with a standard BC Parks sign at the entrance. There is a bright yellow security gate that can be closed when the launch is not open. The directory board near the launch area is on level ground, but access may be limited by parking curbs. Information includes advisories related to boating.
Jade Bay has a large paved parking lot, with stalls long enough to accommodate vehicles and boat trailers. There are no designated accessible parking stalls in this parking lot.

There are very few exterior pathways at Jade Bay. The pathway to the pit toilet is firm and stable, but may have a bit of a side slope. The beach can be access by ground that is loose sand and gravel. Other amenities such as garbage receptacles and the directory board are adjacent to the paved parking lot.

There are two garbage and recycling receptacles at Jade Bay, located adjacent to the paved parking lot. These receptacles have standard wildlife-proof design, that may or may not be operable for people with limited dexterity. One has clear access from the front and the sides; access to the other may be limited by concrete parking curbs.

There is one pit toilet located along a short path from the corner of the parking lot. There is a slight threshold between the path and the concrete pad at the entrance. The door is wide and swings out; the exterior of the door has a large D-handle, and the locking mechanism is dead-bolt style. Interior dimensions are approximately 1.5 x 1.5 m. Grab bars are installed behind and beside the toilet. Toilet paper is closed-roll style, and is mounted above the side grab bar.
The ?attention boaters? sign is mounted above 1500mm height.

Jade Bay includes a boat launch and two floating docks, one on each side of the launch. The launch itself is concrete and slopes into the water. Access to the docks have varying degrees of slope and cross-slope, as well as drop-off areas with no edge protection beside the concrete approach path. The docks themselves are several meters wide, with minimal edge protection. There is no seating or shelter at the boat launch.

Maple Bay Picnic Grounds and Maple Bay Campground are both accessed directly from Columbia Valley Highway, with large colour-contrasted BC Parks signs at the entrance. All entrances have bright yellow security gates. The entrance to the campground clearly indicates the locations of numbered campsites. The directory board in the campground has general camping information but does not include a map; a directory board at the beach in the Picnic Area includes a map of all areas of Maple Bay.

Maple Bay Picnic Grounds has three large paved parking lots, including over 200 parking stalls. There is one designated accessible stall in the third lot, with no signage at the entrance to show its location.
Signage at entrance to picnic area and at entrance to campground.
Exterior pathways are generally wide and paved, but often have significant slopes of up to 18%.

Campsites in Maple Bay Campground are large with firm and level surfaces, although entrances to the sites have slopes of up to 18%. Picnic tables may have shelves for barbecues, but do not have accessible overhanging ends. Fire pits are standard design, and have cooking grids.

There are over 40 picnic tables in the Day Use area, all mounted on concrete pads, some located in a grassy area and others on a large area of hard-packed gravel. There is ample clear space around all tables. None of these tables have accessible overhangs.
Water stand pipes are located throughout the campground and picnic areas. Some have clear level access, but access to others may be limited by raised drains.

Garbage and recycling receptacles are located throughout the campground and day use area. All are wildlife-proof design and may be difficult for people with limited dexterity to operate. Locations of receptacles vary as to ease of access and clear space at front and side.

Pit toilet in the Day Use area is located along gravel pathways, with the concrete pad at the door creating a threshold of up to 50 mm. The door is wide and swings outward, and interior dimensions are approximately 1.5 x 1.5 m. Grab bars are installed behind and beside the toilet. The toilet paper dispenser is closed-roll style, and is mounted forward of the grab bar. Signage on the door does not indicate that this pit toilet has any accessibility features. There is also a pit toilet near the boat launch parking lot which has a wide door and large interior dimensions.

Several washroom and shower buildings are located in the campground, as well as in the Day Use area. Approach paths to the washroom buildings in the campground may have slopes much greater than 8%. Privacy screens at the entrances to these buildings creating sharp corners. These buildings include accessible toilet stalls which may or may not meet current standards of accessibility.
Directional signage is colour contrasted and has large font.
The picnic shelter is accessible. Currently no accessible style tables at this location.

Spring Bay Picnic Area is accessed directly from Columbia Valley Road. Coming from the north, a parks sign is mounted on low posts, on the opposite side of the road, pointing to the parking lot. There is no signage from the south. This parking lot has neither security gates nor a directory board.
Spring Bay offers 14 parking spots, none of which are designated as accessible. The lot provides direct access to picnic tables, the pit toilet, garbage receptacles, and the lake.

A paved pathway connects most of the features in this small Day Use area. The path has minimal slope, but includes some cracking and root upheavals. Edges of the path are sometimes raised above the surrounding grassy area. Two small concrete bridges that cross a stream have edge protection, but include erosion of the edge of the path at the approach, which may make it too narrow for people using wheeled mobility aids.
Eight picnic tables are located on level grassy ground, near the accessible pathway. None of these tables have an accessible overhanging end. Some tables include a metal shelf for a barbecue.

Garbage and recycling receptacles are placed adjacent to the accessible pathway. They have standard wildlife-proof design, which may or may not be operable for people with limited dexterity. A slight difference in height between the pathway and the ground the receptables are on may make it difficult for someone using a wheeled mobility aid to access these receptacles.

There is one pit toilet in this Day Use area, located just off the paved path, on a path that is packed gravel and has some slope. The concrete pad creates a threshold of approximately 70 mm. The door is wide and swings out, and the interior dimensions of this pit toilet are approximately 1.5 x 1.5 m. Grab bars are installed behind and beside the toilet. The toilet paper dispenser is closed-roll style, and is mounted forward of the grab bar. Locking mechanism is a slide-drop latch. Signage on the door of the toilet does not show that it includes any accessibility features.
Cross-hatching between designated stalls provides safe and direct access to pedestrian pathways.

This park is accessed from Highway 16 via Telkwa High Road and Tyhee Road, with clear signage for the turnoff on Highway 16. The entrance sign for the park has large font, but colour contrasting is fading. This park has a bright yellow security gate with a yellow and black reflective closed sign.
Accessible stall surface is level, stable, firm and slip resistant. It is concrete and has minimal to no cross slope. The surface is in good repair with minimal cracking.
Vertical signs clearly identify the accessible stalls. Surface paint signage is worn in all stalls and may be hard to read.

There are four accessible stalls at the Davis parking area. They have both vertical and horizontal markings. There are two sets of two accessible stalls, with 5 m x 5. 8 m cross hatching between the stalls in both sets.
Accessible parking stalls are 3.4 m wide and 5.8 m long.
Entrance signage includes a directory board with a map of the park and general information. There are also signs pointing out the location of numbered campsites.
Exterior pathways between all main features of the park are generally wider than 1.2 m and have surfaces that are level, stable, firm and slip resistant with minimal slope.

There is a set of concrete stairs between the parking lot and the day use beach; alternate accessible pathways exist. Steps are uniform in rise and run, but there are no tactile or colour contrast indicators on the nosings of the steps, nor at the top of the stairs. Grippable handrails are provided, but they do not extend horizontally beyond the top step, and they end at the bottom step rather than on level ground.

The standard campsites at this park have large surface areas with diameters of 8 to 12 m, firmly packed gravel surfaces, and are mostly level, but with a slope of far greater than 1 to 12 from the parking spaces. All sites have standard picnic tables with the exception of site 15 which has a table with an accessible overhanging end. There are four tenting only sites, one of which has a table with an accessible overhanging end. Sites also have fire pits with cooking grates at the back. Campsite numbers are mounted on low wooden posts at the entrance to the site. Numbers have large font and are colour contrasted with the background.
There are a number of water stand pipes in this park. Spout heights range from 750 to 930 mm. Operating mechanisms are accessible hand levers.

An outdoor rinsing shower is provided at the day use area above the beach. It has three heights of shower - one for feet, one at a medium height, and one at the top of the shower stand. Controls are pushbutton style, with heights ranging from 860 mm to 1 m. These controls require significant manual force and dexterity to operate.

A number of picnic tables are located in a grassy area between the picnic shelter and the lake. They are not connected to an accessible pathway, but can be reached across level and firm grass. There is ample clear space around each table. None of these tables have accessible overhanging ends.
Garbage and recycling receptacles are located at various areas throughout the park. All are the standard BC Parks wildlife-proof design, and have clear ground space to the front and side.
The benches placed around the fire pit have no armrests or backrests.

Non-accessible pit toilets in the campground and at the day use area have interior dimensions of 1.3 x 1.3 m. The non-accessible toilets at the boat launch are 1.1 x 1.4 m. Door clearance for these toilets ranges from 560 mm to 620 mm.ėOne set of designated accessible pit toilets are located at near the group camp. They have interior dimensions of 1.5 x 1.5 m and door clearance of 880 mm. Grab bars heights range from 840 mm to 895 mm. Accessible pit toilets have multiple coats hooks hung at 1.3 and 1.7 m. Toilet height in these pit toilets range from 385 mm to 600 mm.ė

An accessible shower room is provided adjacent to site 15 at the campground. The entry door has a level threshold, a lever handle and door clearance of 870 mm. The change area and shower area are separated by a moveable shower curtain with not threshold between the two. There is adequate turning clearance in this area. The changing area has a shelf for personal items install at 1.3 m and three large clothing hooks installed at the same height. There is a pull-down bench with seat height of 490 mm with a grab bar on the side wall mounted at 810 mm. The shower area also has a pull-down seat and grab bars similar in height to those in the change area. The shower controls are difficult to operate, requiring significant force to use, and with the water turning off quite quickly. A handheld or moveable height showerhead is not provided.

A change house is located at the day use area. Signage on the doors uses universally recognizable symbols in high colour contrast, as well as Braille. The change rooms are connected to an accessible pathway and have level entry. The exterior doors have lever handles. In each change room there is a single sink with knee clearance beneath the counter. An automatic hand dryer is installed on the opposite wall from the sink. Seating is provided at a height of 510 mm. There are no grab bars in the changing area. A child change table is provided in the changing area. The men’s side has one accessible toilet stall with a separate urinal, while the women’s side has one accessible and one standard toilet stall. Interior dimensions of the accessible stalls are 1.5 x 1.5 m. Doors have interior D-handles and sliding lock mechanisms. Grab bars are installed behind and beside the toilet.
Directional signage point the way to numbered campsites.
Amenity signs show the location of water stand pipes and shower rooms.

The day use area has a 7m x 10 m picnic shelter which is connected to an accessible pathway. The floor is smooth finished concrete which is level with the connecting pathway. The picnic shelter has no kitchen facilities such as sink or counter, but there is a wood stove which could be used for cooking.
A picnic shelter is located at the group site. This shelter has a wood stove and a sink counter area. Some of the picnic tables have the extended table top.
The floor surface of the picnic shelter is finished concrete which is in good repair. There is only minor surface cracking.

The viewing area at this park consists of an accessible pathway down to the lakeside. The trail terminates in a clear space at the edge of a marsh from which the marsh section of Tyhee Lake can be observed. There is no platform, seating, or shelter provided.

This park has a boat launch consisting of a concrete launching area with a dock directly beside it. The drop-off edge between the two, as well as the drop-off edge at the approach to the dock, have handrails at a height of 930 mm. Signage at the boat launch area includes a bright yellow warning sign about the use of lifejackets, as well as a sign about how to interact with wildlife.
The trail surface varies but includes sections which are covered in grass and moss and may be slippery, some which have large roots, and some with significant cross slope.

The only signage related to the trail is the name sign where it meets the campground adjacent to site number 20, and on the same post some information about plant life. The trail is also included on the park map, but there is no information provided regarding the trail accessibility details or length.
Although much of the trail has height clearance of more than 2 m, there are significant sections where there are overhanging obstruction such as tree branches.
Although much of the trail is level there are some sections with slope far in excess of 1 to 12.
The trail conditions very along its length but most of it is between 50 cm and 2 m wide.

There is a concession stand called Snack Shack located at the beach day use area. It has a single counter with a height of 1.3 m. It is not connected to the accessible pathway, but can be approached across level firm grassy areas from the accessible pathway.

The playground in the day use area is surrounded by 4 x 4 timbers with a surface material of loose pea gravel. It is accessed from the grass areas with a threshold height of two 4 x 4 posts, or via an accessible pathway with a threshold height of one 4 x 4 post. There are no specific accessible play features in the children’s playground. There is also a volleyball net set up adjacent to the accessible walkway to the beach from the parking lot. There is no accessible pathway from this walkway to the volleyball play area.

The Goldstream Visitor Centre is accessed from the Malahat Highway on Finlayson Arm Road, 16 km north of the campground. There is signage on the highway at 400 m, and a standard BC Parks sign at the turn-off. The directory board has information about the park, but print is small and does not always have good colour contrasting, and the reflective surface may create a glare.
There are two designated accessible parking spots at the visitor centre. For those unable to use the trail from the parking lot, centre staff may allow use of these parking stalls.

The access route is a firm, wide path leading from parking to the visitor centre. The surface is compressed, crushed gravel with only minimal sections of uneven ground. There are several small bridges where the trail crosses a culvert. These areas do not have guard rails or curbs. The path to the viewing area has two sections of boardwalk that have a raised threshold, and the viewing area has a raised threshold.
Ramps are in place to enter the Visitor Centre and the washroom building. The surface of the ramp is firm and stable. Slopes exceed 8%, and not all ramps have adequate handrails.

Short flights of stairs are found near the visitor centre. Rise and run may be inconsistent, and there are no colour contrasting nosings or handrails at these stairs. The visitor centre itself is accessed by two steps or a ramp. These steps have open risers, and have no handrails.
There are a number of picnic tables outside the visitor centre. There is a threshold of up to 100 mm to access this area.
There is a drinking fountain located near the washrooms, mounted on the wall. It does not provide clear space for access for persons using a mobility device, and is not colour contrasted.

There are very few seating areas along the 600 metre trail, placed on firm and level ground at the edge of the trail. Benches have back rests, but only some of them have arm rests. Seating at the visitor centre varies in seat height and in availability of arm rests. At the fire pit, benches are located on firm crushed gravel, and have neither back rests nor arm rests.

The washroom building has clear signage showing that it includes accessibility features. Access to the building is via a ramp. The designated accessible stall has ample clear space beside the toilet, and includes an angled side grab bar but no rear grab bar. The toilet paper dispenser is closed-roll style, mounted forward of the grab bar. In the sink area, there is counter space beside the sinks and knee clearance below. The soap dispenser is touch-controlled and is mounted on the back wall above the counter.

The signage throughout this area of the park is easy to locate, but does not always give clear directional guidance at decision-making points. Some signage may be difficult to read because of small font size or minimal colour contrasting.
The lookout area itself is an accessible wooden structure with bench seating and a view of the Goldstream River estuary.

The visitor centre is a great and educational place for kids, families and adults alike. Access to the building is by ramp or two steps, and there is a threshold of approximately 100 mm at the door. There are many exhibits in the learning centre and most are accessible and interactive. The access aisles are wide enough to allow access throughout the visitor centre. For children who are unable to access the centre, adaptive programming for schools is available. If people are unable to travel the access trail to reach the visitor centre because of a mobility issue, the centre can provide instructions to allow vehicle access for short visits.

The campground at Goldstream is located in the far southwest of the park, accessed via Golden Gate Road. The entrance to the park includes a standard BC Parks sign and a high visibility yellow security gate. The gate house is located at the entrance to the campground and is staffed according to the seasons. The gate house provides access to the ice machine and basic convenience store services. The entrance doorway is narrow and has a low threshold. The directory board includes maps of the park and the general area, as well as hiking information. There is a payphone beside the directory board; this phone may be difficult to operate for people with limited dexterity, or those in a seated position.
While the route from the Malahat Highway to the campground is not straightforward, there is clear signage along the way at all decision points.

The access routes through the campground are generally wide, firm and stable with minimum slope. All roads connecting campers to washrooms and service areas are paved and level. All paths are level and firm with a surface of compressed, crushed gravel.
Three campsites have newly built stairs to access the site. These stairs are firm and stable, and have consistent rise and run, but do not have handrails.

There are seven accessible campsites in Goldstream campground, located close to the shower buildings on the inner loop of the campground, and close to the kids’ play area and amphitheater. Each campsite has a firm, level surface with an accessible picnic table. Rather than having overhanging ends, some of the tables have a section of the side bench removed. Standard fire pits are present. The tenting area is level with the ground. The accessible campsites are 100, 101, 102, 103, 117, 118, and 140.

The regular campsites are well designed with a level, firm surface. Each one has a picnic table and fire pit. Some have raised tent pads. A small number of walk-in campsites are located near Shower Building 1. The access path is firm and level. Several of these sites have raised tent pads. Three campsites have a flight of stairs at the entrance. The stairs are new and are firm and stable, with consistent rise and run, but no handrails.
Water standpipes are located throughout the park, generally on clear and level ground, mounted on a concrete pad.

Garbage and recycling receptacles are located in service areas throughout the campground, as well as near the dishwashing sinks. All have ample clear ground space for access from the front and sides. Operating mechanisms are standard wildlife-proof design that may be difficult for people with limited dexterity to use.

All pit toilets in this campground are located along accessible pathways, generally along with other amenities. Clear signage on the door indicates that they include accessibility features. Door clearance is wide, and there is clear, level ground in front of the door. Interior dimensions are approximately 1.6 x 1.6 m. Grab bars are installed behind and beside the toilet, as well as on the inside of the door. Door locking mechanism is slide lock, which can be operated with a closed fist. Toilet paper dispensers are closed-roll style, and are mounted forward of the side grab bar.

There are a number of washroom/shower buildings buildings in this campground. Both sides include standard-sized shower and toilet stalls. Washrooms are well lit, and include a sink and counter area with clear knee space below. Soap dispensers are push-activated, and are mounted on the wall behind the sinks. An automatic hand dryer is on the side wall at one end of the counter. All toilet buildings include a baby change table. Each building also includes separate universal washroom/shower rooms that can only be accessed using a code obtained from the gate house. The toilet and shower areas are separated by a partial wall; the toilet area is at least 1.5 x 1.5 m, and includes rear and side grab bars. The toilet paper dispenser is closed-roll style, mounted above the side grab bar.

Each shower building includes several standard-sized shower stalls in both sides, but also has a separate universal design toilet and shower room; access to this room requires a code available from the gate house. Shower and toilet areas within these rooms are separated by a wall. The shower is level entry, and includes fold-down seating, a side grab bar with a 90-degree angle, a shower head that is adjustable in height and can be handheld.
Directional signs within the park have good colour contrasting and use both text and symbols. Font is somewhat small to be read from a vehicle.

The amphitheatre is located at the center of the campground, near the playground and bike course. The surface of the amphitheater is level and firm. The seating has wide aisles, but benches do not have back support or arm rests.

The Upper Goldstream hiking trail is steep in places with rocky inclines and a path that is broken and uneven. The signage relating to the trails is posted high and may be difficult to read. There are no accessible trails that transect or commence from the Goldstream Campground .
A dishwashing and food prep station is available at the shower buildings. The sink and counters do not have clear knee space under them; taps have levered handles.

A playground and bike trail are located in the center of the campground. The bike trail is suitable for novice to expert riders. There is clear signage related to the bike track. The playground is large and includes a variety of equipment, most of which requires climbing. The outer edge of the playground has a threshold, sometimes up to 200 mm high. Surface under the play equipment is soft natural materials. There are picnic tables and benches on crushed gravel pathways around the playground. One of the tables has a cut-out section to allow access for a wheeled mobility device.

The picnic area at Goldstream is accessed directly from the Malahat Highway via Finlayson Arm Road, sharing a parking lot with the visitor centre. There is approach signage on the highway, and a standard BC Parks sign at the turn-off. The directory board is located in the first parking lot, and includes maps of the park and information about the area. Not all information is colour contrasted, and font is sometimes small.
The picnic area and visitor’s centre has only two disability parking stalls. There is no disability parking near the viewing areas or trail head to the visitor centre.
The trail from parking to the picnic area wide and level in most areas, with a surface of hard-packed crushed gravel.

The picnic area has several dozen picnic tables located along the perimeter of the parking lot and around the central picnic shelter. The surface under these tables varies from hard-packed gravel to loose gravel. All are mounted on concrete pads, some of which are above grade by up to 80 mm.

Garbage and recycling receptacles located in the parking lot area on firm and level ground, with access from front and sides. All are standard wildlife-proof design which may be difficult for people with limited dexterity to operate. The receptacles near the picnic shelter are within a wooden structure and can only be accessed from the front.
There is an accessible drinking fountain located by the washrooms. Access is via a concrete sidewalk and there’s a push button water control.

The washrooms are located centrally in the main picnic area. Each washroom includes a designated accessible stall, which has ample floor space, side and rear grab bars, and sensor flushing mechanism. The sink area has counter space on both sides of the sink and knee clearance beneath. The faucet is sensor controlled; the soap dispenser is push-activated, and is mounted quite high on the wall behind the sink. Lighting levels within these washrooms is low.
Directional signage has good colour contrasting, but the font may be somewhat small for signs that are expected to be read from a moving vehicle.

The picnic shelter is a large structure with a roof but no walls, allowing for multiple access points. The concrete floor surface is firm and level and in good repair. Of the eight picnic tables within this structure, five of them have accessible overhanging ends. All have ample clear space around them. There are also a wood burning stove and sink area available. The sink area has ample counter space, with knee clearance below. Taps are push-style. The picnic area has two fire pits.

The viewing area by the river has a surface of loose gravel and is uneven. There is a modest slope down to the shore of the river. The information sign on fish species is informative and easy to read, but with small print. It is located close to the trail to the picnic area. The viewing area in the picnic area gives an excellent view of the river and surrounding shoreline. The surface is even and firm, using a compressed crushed gravel surface. The single bench in the area provides proper arm and back support.

The group campsites at Goldstream are accessed directly from the Malahat Highway, with a standard BC Parks sign at the entrance. There is a directory board in each of the parking lots at Goldminer and Prospector, which can be accessed on firm and level ground.They include a map of the park, and information about wildlife in the area. Font is very small, and there may be some glare on these signs.

Parking is available near the entrances to both group campsites. Lots are large and level, with surfaces of crushed gravel that are firm and stable. There are no designated accessible parking stalls at either of these sites.
The access routes through Prospector group campsite are all accessible with level, firm surfaces. The tenting area is hard packed earth and grass which is fairly level in most areas.

While neither of these group campsites is designated as accessible, Prospector site has fully accessible routes, pit toilets, fire pit and picnic shelter. There is plenty of space for parking but no designated accessible stalls. The fire pit at Prospector group campsite is located near the picnic shelter. It has an accessible path and wide access around the pit. The seating is simple and does not have back rests or armrests.

The Goldminer site has fewer accessibility features compared to the Prospector group campsite. Goldminer picnic shelter and fire pit have raised thresholds around their perimeter, and are only accessible via a single path if using a mobility device. The access aisle around the fire pit is wide. Only two of the pit toilets are accessible.
Both sites have water stand pipes which can be accessed on level ground. Taps require grip and dexterity to operate.

Garbage and recycling receptacles are located at each site, in clear open space, mounted on concrete pads. The pad at Goldminer is approximately 80 mm above grade, while that at Prospector is level with the surrounding ground. All receptacles are standard wildlife-proof design that may be difficult to operate for people with limited dexterity.

There are 4 pit toilets at Goldminer, two in the tenting area and two near the parking lot. None of these toilets are connected to accessible pathways, but all have interior dimensions of approximately 1.5 x 1.5 m, and grab bars behind and beside the toilet. Toilet paper dispensers are closed-roll style, mounted forward of the side grab bar. Locking mechanisms require grip and dexterity to operate. Prospector also has four pit toilets, two in the camping area and two near the picnic shelter. All are connected to accessible pathways, with interiors similar to those at Goldminer.

Both group campsites include large picnic shelters and outdoor picnic areas. The shelter at Goldminer has a raised threshold from the grassy field, but has level access from the crushed gravel walkway. Both shelters have a variety of picnic tables, including some with accessible overhanging ends. Tables can be moved around to create access aisles as required. Shelters include wood burning stoves, and sinks with counter space but no knee clearance. Taps at Goldminer may be difficult to use for people with limited dexterity.

Sasquatch Park is located off of Highway 7. Signs indicate travel route through Harrison Hot Springs, onto Rockwell Dr. and through Green Point Day Use area. Deer Lake is located beyond the Hicks Lake turn-off, approximately a half hour drive from Harrison Hot Springs.

The gravel lot at the Deer Lake boat launch has 15 spots for parking, some of which can accommodate large vehicles. There is an empty lot at Bench Campground for extra vehicles to park. No stalls are currently designated as accessible.

All the main paths and access routes around the campgrounds and boat launch area are compacted crushed gravel, and are wide with minimal slope. A short wooden boardwalk leading away from the boat launch has some small gaps between planks which should be taken into consideration for those who have mobility issues.

Lakeside Campground offers 42 vehicle accessible campsites, while Bench Campground has 64 sites. Each site is large enough for several tents, and has a picnic table and fire pit. Picnic tables have accessible overhanging ends. The surface for every campsite is compacted gravel and dirt, both in the campground and on the access routes.
Both campgrounds offer plenty of water standpipes which are conveniently spaced out among the campsites. Some are hand pumps which require significant strength and overhead reach to operate.

Both campgrounds offer plenty of garbage and recycling receptacles which are conveniently spaced out among the campsites, often locate on concrete pads which may have thresholds up to 100 mm. Most have clear access from front and sides. Operating mechanism is standard wildlife-proof design. Garbage cans are located at the boat launch.

Pit toilets are located throughout both campgrounds. Most access pathways are crushed gravel and have minimal slope. Some have thresholds at the entrance. Interior dimensions are approximately 1.5 x 1.5 m, doors open out and are about 850 mm wide. Grab bars are installed behind and beside the toilet. Toilet paper dispensers are closed-roll style, mounted forward of the side grab bar.
The Deer Lake section of the park has signs that are conveniently located at the main entrance area of the park. Signs have good colour contrast.
There is a playground at Lakeside Campground, down a slight slope from the pathway. Surface under the playground is soft materials.

Green Point Day Use Area is located within Sasquatch Park, with clear signage through Harrison Hot Springs, and accessed via Rockwell Road. A directory board at the entrance includes information about the park and the general area.

The parking lot at this Day Use area is paved with a flat surface throughout. Some stalls can accommodate extra large vehicles such as vans, trucks, or buses. Of the more than 200 parking stalls, four are designated as accessible. These four stalls have blue painted surface sigange, but no vertical signage. Stalls are somewhat wider than regular stalls, but do not have access aisles.
Most of the main access routes are paved asphalt with minimal slope. The pathways to the washroom building, however, have greater slopes and some areas of root upheavals.

The main picnic area closest to the parking lot offers 27 tables on flat and level ground, located along an accessible pathway, with ample clear space around each one. None of these tables have accessible overhangs. More tables of a similar style are located further down the path on the other side of the day use area, near the pit toilet.
Green Point offers plenty of water standpipes which are conveniently spaced out around the grounds. The vast majority are on a flat level surface and easy to access.

Garbage and recycling receptacles are conveniently spaced out around the Day Use area. While the majority are on a flat level surface and easy to access, some may be on uneven grassy ground. All are standard wildlife-proof design.

Green Point offers two pit toilets located on hard packed gravel pathways which may have some slope. Doors are wide and open out, and interior dimensions are approximately 1.5 x 1.5 m. One has a side grab bar installed on the far side from the toilet, and no rear grab bar. The toilet paper dispenser is closed-roll style.
Clear signs at the turn-off to the Day Use area use both words and symbols, and have good colour contrasting.

This Day Use area offers fantastic views of Harrison Lake. While there is not one designated viewing area, there are plenty of areas to get a good view while at a picnic table. The areas that do provide the best views are of a flat and level surface, with easy access for those using a mobility device.
There is a boat launch at Green Point. High visibility yellow parking curbs delineate the entrance to the boat launch.
Hicks Lake is located within Sasquatch Park, with clear signage through Harrison Hot Springs, along Rockwell Drive. The directory board at the entrance includes a map of the campground.

Both campgrounds provide a hard compacted gravel surface on all the roads, including into the campsites themselves. Access routes to the pit toilets, garbage and recycling receptacles, and water standpipes are made of the same surface, are generally wide and have minimal slopes.

Hicks Lake campground offers 71 campsites, each with enough room for multiple tents. The surface for every campsite is compacted gravel and dirt, both in the campground and on the access routes. Sites include picnic tables, most with accessible overhangs, and standard fire pits with cooking grids. Hicks Lake Group Site can accommodate 15 - 40 people. There is a picnic shelter, fire pit, two pit toilets, raised tenting pads, drinking water, and a small parking area.
A picnic area near Hicks Lake Trail has six tables, most on firm and level ground. None of them have accessible overhanging ends. There are also standard tables in the group campsite.
Water standpipes are located throughout the various areas of the park, generally on level ground with room for approach.

Garbage and recycling receptacles are conveniently spaced out around the main campground, group campground, boat launch area, and picnic area. All are standard wildlife-proof design, and are accessible from the front and at least one side.

Hicks Lake offers pit toilets throughout all areas of the park. Most can be accessed on pathways that are wide and have minimal slope. Some toilets have thresholds at the entrance. Most have adequate interior transfer space, wide doors that open out, and grab bars beside and behind the toilet. Toilet paper dispensers are closed-roll style, mounted forward of the side grab bar.
Hicks Lake has signs that are conveniently located at the main entrance area. Signs are well colour contrasted, include both words and symbols, and are easy to read from a vehicle.

The picnic shelter is located at the group site on the other side of Hicks Lake. There is some unevenness at the entrance. It is spacious and has 13 tables both inside and outside, none of which have accessible overhangs. There are no kitchen facilities, but a wood stove could be used for cooking.

This park has one boat launch area which provides lake access and a view spot. There is also a good spot to view the lake near the picnic area at Hicks Lake Trail. There is an empty lot nearby the boat launch area although specific parking spaces are not established.
BC Parks signage identifies park entrance. The park information kiosk provides information on the history of the park as well as park map and trail information.

Access from road to gate house is paved asphalt with painted center line distinguishing the two lanes. Access loop through camp ground to walk-in camp area is a well maintained asphalt surface. Routes are wide enough for two vehicles to pass one another with ease. Access routes are smooth with gradual slopes. Washrooms are located along access routes, with flat well maintained pathways leading to the washroom facilities. Access route to washroom facility from east side is very narrow, has severe side slope and may be difficult to use by person using mobility aid. One of the rent-able Legacy Cabins has a gentle ramp to the front of the cabin; however there is a small threshold at the front door that may pose difficulty for persons using mobility aids to access. There is no accessible route down to the beach in the viewing area. The route is steep at points and often obstructed with depressions, rocks and trees.

Two rent-able Legacy Cabins are available on site. The cabin interior has limited clear space and persons using mobility aids may have difficulty accessing features within the cabins. The legacy cabins are former Olympic village cabins moved to Porteau Cove Park and available for rent through the park. The interior of the cabin is cozy and the main room provides enough space for turning. The bottom bedroom is accessible and has just enough room for transfer. Only one cabin is wheelchair accessible via an access ramp.

Campsite surfaces are packed gravel and well maintained. Picnic tables are fixed to concrete pads. Campsites do not include tent pads, but the sites are very level, with minimal cross slope. Most campsites are large enough to park a small RV. There are no designated accessible campsites, however most campsites can support a van equipped with a ramp, and are near the washroom facility. Garbage facilities and water standpipes are located throughout the campsite.

Picnic tables in campsites do not include a large overhang to accommodate persons using mobility aids. Some of the picnic tables in the viewing area are fully accessible and are all located adjacent parking and close to the pier. The surface area around each table is compressed gravel that provides adequate firmness for any mobility device or stroller.

There are two water stand pipes and one water fountain at the site. There is a smooth and even surface around the stand pipes, but the tap control is not lever-type and may be difficult to operate. Drain grates at water standpipes may have openings around 13mm.

Garbage receptacles are located next to the access route, fastened to the ground, and cane detectable. They are not colour-contrasted with the surroundings, and they have wildlife-proof latches that may be difficult to open.
The seating on the pier is located for easy access there are no arm rests. The seating offers firm back support and good seat height.

A pit toilet is located adjacent to the toilet facility. Some accessible features can be found in the toilet facility including: rear and side grab bars, a large entry door and a grab bar mounted on the entry door. The toilet paper dispenser is mounted above grab bar.

The washroom facility is located at the center of the campsite loop within a reasonable distance to all campsites. The entrance area has limited clear space and may be difficult for persons using mobility devices to access. No automatic door opener is installed on the washroom door. The washroom door requires significant effort to open, due to the door closing device. The washroom counter includes appropriate knee space and counter height. Faucet control is operable with a closed fist. Hand soap is mounted on wall behind sink and may be difficult to reach from a seated position. Two heights of urinals are available in male washroom, but are not equipped with mobility grab bars. Toilet grab bar on side wall does not extend beside the side of toilet. Toilet paper holder is mounted above grab bar and may be difficult to reach from the seated position. Toilet flush mechanism is located on the non-transfer side of the toilet and may be difficult to reach from the seated position. Doors to accessible washroom stalls don’t have d-ring style handles. Many washroom coat hooks are mounted high on washroom walls and may not be accessible from a seated position.

Washroom shower stalls include seating and two grab bars. The shower control is operable with a closed fist but is not operable while seated on shower bench. Shower head is mounted high and is not adjustable from seated position. The shower bench creates a pinch point at the shower wall, which may prevent persons using mobility aids from entering accessible shower. The shower stall clothing hooks are mounted high on shower walls and are not within reach while in seated position.

A park information board is located at the entrance to the public use area along access route to the campsite gate. Maps and informational signage on the board. Campsite signage indicating pricing and hours are located at the gate. Campsite numbering and directional signage are located along vehicular access route. Signage is consistent and understandable. Symbols are utilized where possible. Washroom signage is mounted on the washroom structure but may not obviously visible from the vehicular route.
The pier is fully accessible and has numerous seating areas and viewing areas offering an excellent view of the cove. The viewing platforms are only accessed via stairs.

Porteau Cove Park - Boat Launch is accessed directly from the Sea to Sky highway. The parking lot is shared with Porteau Cove Park. While there are accessible stalls in the lot, they are on the opposite side of the lot from the boat launch. There are two designated parking stalls with painted access symbols on asphalt, located near the washroom building. Parking stalls are long enough for vehicle and trailer combination.
There are two designated accessible parking stalls near the washroom building. These stalls are identified with surface signage.
The directory board is located near the washroom building and adjacent the parking lot.

Access from the parking areas to the public use washroom is a solid surface; however there are some cracks and uneven portions. The walkways are narrow and don’t allow users to easily pass one another. There are two picnic table areas adjacent to the public use parking areas, with one having an accessible pathway. The pathway to the pier runs near the picnic table and is separate from the parking lot; the surface is compacted gravel with some loose gravel on top. The pier walkway is very wide and stable. Bench seating is evenly dispersed down the length of the pier.

There is a concrete staircase leading into the water. It has a railing on one side but does not have colour-contrasting stairs. There are three raised viewing areas accessed via stairs. The steps to the lookout areas on the pier have a graspable railing and the surface of the steps includes diamond plate steel for traction; the steps are an open riser style.

Picnic tables are provided on grassy areas adjacent to parking areas. The pathway surface from the parking area to the picnic tables is gravel that is well packed and firm. There is one designated accessible picnic table with a longer overhang. The picnic tables are set on concrete pads; however, the pad is not large enough to accommodate a wheelchair. The area surrounding the picnic table pad is often 2-3 inches lower than the top of the pad surface and may not allow a person in a wheelchair to properly approach and use the picnic tables.

Water standpipe is located adjacent the public washrooms. The path surface leading to the standpipe is hard packed and easily accessible from parking lot. The standpipe control is a knob style and very stiff. The control is a self-closing style and requires constant user pressure to maintain a continuous flow of water.

There is an outdoor shower next to the boat launch. It has a clear area with smooth, stable ground. There are shower heads for rinsing feet, as well as a full-body shower head. Shower controls are very high and not operable from a seated position. These controls are knob style and not operable with a closed fist.
Animal resistant garbage receptacles are located near public parking areas along paved pathway. The animal resistant opening mechanism is operable with a closed fist.
Benches are provided on the pier and the viewing platforms.

The washroom facility entrance areas are quite narrow and may be difficult to maneuver through. Washrooms do not have a power door and the door closers make the washroom doors heavy. Washroom vanities have knee space below sink. Faucet operation is an automatic sensor. Hand dryers are mounted on wall behind sink and may be difficult to reach for a person in a seated position. Hand soap dispensers are at good heights, are easily operable with a closed fist, and are within reach of a person in a seated position. Coat hooks in washroom stalls are high and a person in a seated position would not be able to reach hook. Accessible stall has room within to maneuver around. Grab bars are installed on rear and side walls of accessible stall. Toilet paper dispensers are mounted high on side wall and could be difficult to reach from seated position. Toilet flush mechanisms are located on non-transfer side of toilet and may be difficult to reach for a person in a seated position.

The park information board is located at the entrance to the public use area. Directional and informational signage content is generally easy to read and understand. Sign locations are logical and at a good height.

There are several natural viewing areas on access routes along the water’s edge. The pier has many lookout areas at ground level and raised platforms that require stairs to access. Most railings along the viewing area are not graspable. Raised viewing areas would be difficult to access for persons with limited mobility. There are no lowered railing areas along the pier to allow unobstructed views or fishing from a seated position.

The parking lot is paved, level and in good repair. There are ample parking stalls to accommodate visitors, including persons with a disability; however, none are designated or marked as accessible. This area is separate from the day-use area, and is generally used as a parking lot for divers.

The divers entrance is located to the right of the boat launch. The entrance consists of a set of stairs descending into the water with a single handrail for support. The access route from the washroom to the parking lot is short, level, and made of asphalt.
Garbage receptacles are located adjacent the parking area and access may be limited by curbs. The receptacles have grass surface surroundings.

The Diver’s Building washrooms are located just inside the highway entrance to the park. The entrances are level and swing doors have high resistance door closers. The turning radius through the doorways is quite narrow and therefore persons with limited mobility may have difficulty navigating the entrances. Each washroom is equipped with an accessible toilet stall. Accessible toilet stall is large enough for person with mobility aid to freely move, and to position on transfer side of toilet to utilize grab bars on rear and side walls to transfer onto toilet. The sink area faucet is push activated and may stay on requiring multiple uses to complete hand washing. The hand dryer is mounted to back wall and may be difficult to reach for a person in a seated position.
There are limited wayfinding signs indicating what the Diver’s Building area is for as you enter from the highway. The existing signs have large, colour-contrasting letters that are easy to read.

A walk-in parking area is located close to the walk-in campsite area, approximately 200 meters from the walk-in campsites.The parking lot is constructed with asphalt and has no significant slopes. The access route into the walk-in campground is accessible and has a firm surface of crushed gravel. It is a short distance of several hundred feet to reach the campsite and picnic shelter from the parking area. Visitors who wish to visit the walk-in campsite area are required to park at the day-use parking area and walk to the walk-in campsites.

Access to the walk-in campsites is located along the drive-in campsite loop. The paths to access the walk-in campsites are firm with only minor changes in slope. The surface is compressed crushed gravel. The pedestrian route from the walk-in parking area to the walk-in campsites is gently sloped up to the campsites. The pedestrian route has several uneven areas and tree roots along the path of travel. The walk-in area of the park has compacted dirt and gravel for its access routes which is relatively easy to maneuver around. This includes routes around the parking lot, pit toilets, campsites, picnic shelter, and garbage/recycling receptacles. A steeply sloped pathway provides access to the view point.

The walk-in campsites are divided between level access (land side) and sloped access (water side). Campsites located in the walk-in campsite area are smaller than the campsites located in the drive-in campsite area. These campsites are more uneven but include level tent pads. No picnic tables are located on the walk-in sites but there are small benches fixed in place on concrete pads. Surface material is packed stone and well maintained.

The walk-in campground is serviced by 3 water supply areas; one at the entrance to the campground, one on the lower path below the campsites and one in the picnic shelter via the kitchen area. A water standpipe is located near the walk-in campsites. The standpipe controls are not operable with a closed fist and are self-closing. Constant physical pressure is required to maintain water flow. The standpipe pads are level with the access paths.
Garbage receptacles are animal proof and are operable with a closed fist. There is a small step required to get onto the garbage bin pad from the access route.
Benches located in the campsite area are fixed to concrete pads. The campsite benches to do not have backrests or armrests.

Two pit toilet facilities are located close to the campsites. These pit toilets are situated on concrete pads. Some accessible features can be found in the pit toilet facility located behind the picnic shelter, including: rear and side grab bars, and a grab bar mounted on the entry door. The toilet paper dispensers are mounted above grab bar.

Directional signage guides park users along the access road within the park to the walk-in campsite area. Directional signs use symbols and are easy to understand. The pit toilets do not have any obvious information or directional signage to direct users to their location. No signage is installed to indicate pit toilets which also include accessible features. The access route to the lookout point near the walk-in campsites does not indicate the level of difficulty or the slope of the pathway.

A covered picnic shelter with sinks and faucets is located near the walk-in campsites. The shelter has a concrete floor with picnic tables fixed in place. There is limited open space to move between the picnic tables. The shelter is accessed via a pedestrian route from the walk-in campsites and is located adjacent the vehicular access. The shelter pad has slight threshold difference with the surrounding ground surface. There are no picnic tables that can accommodate a person using a mobility aid. The food preparation and sink counter is very high and would be difficult to access from a seated position. The knee space below the countertop is very limited. Electrical outlets are mounted on the back-splash of the countertop and would be difficult to access from a seated position. The faucet controls are lever style but the height of the faucet may be difficult to access from a seated position.

Two look-out areas are located near the walk-in campsites. A short bridge spans the lagoon inlet a short distance from the campsites and provides a lookout over the lagoon. This bridge has ramp access on one side only, but has three steps on the non-ramp side of the bridge. The bridge is stable but narrow and has limited space to maneuver. A high railing along the bridge prevents users from falling off of bridge but the railing is not graspable. No seating is available on or near the bridge. ėA second viewpoint is located south of the walk-in campsites. The access route to the viewpoint is hard packed stone and is wide enough to support two way pedestrian travel. The trailhead is very steep and may pose difficulty for a person using a mobility device to access. A stair system takes users to the top of a lookout platform overlooking Porteau Cove and Howe Sound.
